  {
    "reg_id": "REG-025",
    "clause": "Art17(1)",
    "considered_references": [
      "Art21(1)",
      "Art21(2)",
      "Art6(1)",
      "Art9(2)",
      "Art8(1)"
    ],
    "deviation_found": true,
    "deviations": [
      {
        "deviation_type": "Time deviation",
        "analysis": "GDPR requires that, when a data subject objects to processing for direct marketing under Art21(2), the controller must erase personal data \"without undue delay\". Evidence: Art17(1) — \"The data subject shall have the right to obtain from the controller the erasure of personal data concerning him or her without undue delay ... (c) ... or the data subject objects to the processing pursuant to Article 21(2).\" Art21(2) — \"the data subject shall have the right to object at any time to processing ... for such marketing\". The policy instead states it will delete data only when organisational purposes cease, \"generally ... after a period of three years at the end of the year\" following cessation of marketing. This sets a general multi-year timeline rather than erasure without undue delay."
      },
      {
        "deviation_type": "Data deviation",
        "analysis": "Art17(1) mandates erasure of \"personal data\" when the data subject objects under Art21(2). Evidence: Art17(1) — \"the erasure of personal data ... without undue delay ... (c) ... or the data subject objects to the processing pursuant to Article 21(2).\" Art21(2) — right to object to direct marketing. The policy explicitly keeps some personal data beyond objection/withdrawal on a blocking list for documentation/verification and to prevent future marketing. This narrows the scope of erasure by retaining certain personal data instead of erasing them upon a direct-marketing objection."
      },
      {
        "deviation_type": "Data deviation",
        "analysis": "GDPR Art 17(1) lists six independent grounds requiring erasure: \"...where one of the following grounds applies: (a) ... no longer necessary; (b) the data subject withdraws consent ... and where there is no other legal ground; (c) the data subject objects to the processing pursuant to Article 21(1) ... or ... Article 21(2); (d) ... unlawfully processed; (e) ... to be erased for compliance with a legal obligation; (f) ... collected in relation to the offer of information society services referred to in Article 8(1).\" (REG-025; cross‑refs to Art 21(1)/(2) in REG-035/REG-036; Art 8(1) in REG-005; and Art 9(2)(a) as cited within REG-009). The policy states erasure applies only if data are no longer needed or consent is withdrawn, omitting the other four GDPR grounds. This narrows the scope of the right to erasure compared to GDPR’s full set of grounds."
      }
    ],
    "source": [
